Predicting recall RT with 2AFC RT (v2.0B)

March 4, 2021

March 4 update

  • Adding 30 more participants
  • Add simulated pairings analysis

Exclusions

  • Excluding 0 participants who gave incorrect resonses on fewer than 25% of recall trials, leaving 56 participants in the analysis.
  • Dropping 53 recall trials with reaction times over more than 3 sds above the mean (more than 5.6 seconds), leaving 1011 trials in the analysis.

Simulating pairings

For example, x axis are index for 10 pairs ordered by (easy-hard), there is a red line representing easy and blue line representing hard. each data point on red or blue is mean of 30 subjects, then add error bar - then we can see if the blue and red line get more apart as the (easy-hard) is increasing

AFC RT -> Recall RT

We want to see if the reaction time on 2AFC trials for a given word are predictive of reaction time for the same word in the recall task.

Est. S.E. t val. p
(Intercept) 5.313 0.186 28.591 0.000
log_afc_rt 0.291 0.026 11.124 0.000
Standard errors: OLS

This looks promising, but it could be driven by individual differences. We need to see the effect within individuals.

Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 5.791 0.257 22.513 524.274 0.000
log_afc_rt 0.225 0.036 6.265 549.007 0.000
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f.

Looks like we still see a positive relationship. We can visualize it more clearly by applying participant-wise mean centering:

And here is the distribution of slopes (with 95% confidence intervals).

73% of participants have a positive slope. This is a good sign, but its still not great. The estimates are super noisy so its hard to know how much of this is real. Heres a similar plot with the correlation.

AFC accuracy

Est. S.E. t val. p
(Intercept) 7.697 0.106 72.825 0.000
afc_accuracy -0.333 0.109 -3.056 0.002
Standard errors: OLS

This looks promising, but it turns out this one is driven entirely by individual differences (each line is a participant). Mixed effects regression shows no effect of 2AFC trials, especially when we account for RT on the correct 2AFC trials.

Time course

2AFC RT goes down, as we would expect.

Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 5.410 0.316 17.127 420.386 0.000
log_afc_rt1 0.087 0.028 3.145 897.553 0.002
log_afc_rt2 0.089 0.036 2.497 873.248 0.013
log_afc_rt3 0.104 0.038 2.746 933.154 0.006
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f.

The slope appears to be constant over rounds.

lo g_afc_rt1 lo g_afc_rt2 lo g_afc_rt3 lo g_recall_rt
log_afc_rt1 1.0000000 0.4038629 0.3723432 0.2376183
log_afc_rt2 0.4038629 1.0000000 0.6515606 0.2791963
log_afc_rt3 0.3723432 0.6515606 1.0000000 0.2733194
log_recall_rt 0.2376183 0.2791963 0.2733194 1.0000000

But the correlation is higher in rounds 2 and 3. (Look at the last column in the correlation matrix)
